Rating: 4
When I quit my day job and open my restaurant (it can't hurt to dream, can't it), I've found my 2nd recipe for the menu (seared tuna pepper steaks was first - look it up on Epicurious). A couple of tips. I used regular strength chicken stock instead of the low-salt called for (I never think the low-salt has enough flavor). If you don't use low-salt broth, you don't need to salt the pork, as the recipe recommends. I did, and it was a little too salty. Also, my onions could have been chopped a little finer - not too fine, though. Finally, don't skimp on the cranberry sauce. It all cooks up. I think at least 1/2 cup would be fine. Great main dish to serve to impress your friends, and pretty easy to make.

Rating: 0
I haven't tried the recipe yet, but I can speak to the issue of appropriate temperatures for pork and trichinosis. Temperatures between 41-140 degrees are called the Danger Zone and most foods should be kept out of it to prevent food borne illness. Cooking the pork loins to an internal temperature of 155 degrees for 15 SECONDS will destroy most harmful bacteria. I would not cook any pork to less than an internal temp. of 140 degrees. Trichinosis in the U.S. has been greatly reduced, but it has not been completely eliminated. Any meat, pork included, should be handled with care and cooked to a safe internal temperature. All ovens are not created equal, and they cook at different rates. If the timing on this recipe appears to be off, invest in a good oven thermometer and/or have your oven recalibrated. If the pork is not done to one's preference after the requisite cooking time, cook it longer in 5-7 minute increments until it reaches the desired level of doneness.

Rating: 3
I am a health care provider, and Cook from Boston is right; trichinosis was a problem when pigs were fed slop/any human or animal leftovers. Due to modern pig feeding practices, it is quite rare in the US today; the risk is greater in some wild game. Trich, even if present, is killed at a temp of around 137-138 degrees F. One does NOT have to cook pork till it's gray...that is a waste of a good cut of meat.

