I have made this dish many times and always successfully! I substituted thyme for the rosemary and added a little cornstarch to the sauce to make it adhere to the meat better because you can't get too much of it! I have also made the sauce hours ahead for company and just reheated it on the stove with alot of success.

Rating: 4
My husband's highest praise after a fine, home-cooked meal is 2 simple words: "Company dish." And that's what he said while relishing this pork tenderloin. It was a perfect entree: easy to make but with complex, complimentary flavors and aromas. I doubled the recipe for my family of 4, roasted the pork for 20 mins @ 400 instead of 10 mins @ 450 (the butter was smoking too much at the higher heat), and reduced the amount of rosemary to a half Tbs. I also made the sauce in the cast iron pan in which I'd roasted the pork, de-glazing the pan with a little red wine before adding the onions and rosemary. The sauce required at least 15 minutes of cooking-down to reach the desired consistency. The pork was fork-tender, and I believe I could've drunk the sauce from the platter by itself. We'll make this over and over. We served it with creamy mashed potatoes and asparagus roasted with olive oil and sea salt.

